<br>
I had mixed opinions of the preview.  I liked the idea of being able to buy land and build a home I can maintain, but don't like that the banks arent linked - meaning I have to physically move everything from bank to bank via carts and wagons.  Decaying is also not one of my fav things.  I was really looking forward to DAoC but got tired of my gear always having to be replaced.<br>
<br>
The preview also said that originally the SWG and EQ2 folks were pretty much working together, but were split when it became apparent they had different goals.  Its SWG thats supposed to be aimed at the casual gamer - seeing as how many non-RPG folks are going to be drawn in by the mere fact the word Star Wars is in the title.  Seeing as how EQ2 will be for the more 'power-gamer', it has the higher system req.<br>
<br>
Overall, Im intriqued but hesitant to get my hopes up.  Ill buy it, play it, and if I dont like it thats ok too - Im not quitting EQ1 and theres SWG and WoW and porn........<br>
<br>
<br>
phengurz <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ujblackfoot.showPublicProfile?language=EN>J Blackfoot</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 25<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/29/02 11:35:54 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2434.topic&index=42>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Be honest</span><hr size=1> One factor that will affect the success of EQ2 is the amount of content they include at release.<br>
<br>
MMRPG players are much more sophisticated now than when the original EQ was released. They play longer and put more effort into mastering all the aspects of the game design. They are more demanding. The genre isn't new anymore. So the games have to have more substance and be more finished than they did when EQ1 was released.<br>
<br>
You can see this illustrated clearly in the how typical cross-gamers view DAoC and the current EQ. You have DAoC, which is a better designed game than EQ, and really more fun, but it's lack of content is causing players to return to play EQ. Players burn through the content in DAoC in a couple of months and return to EQ because there's nothing new to do in DAoC. And, the amount of content that was in EQ when it was released is comparable to the amount of content in DAoC when it was released.<br>
<br>
EQ increases it's longevity by building in time-consuming, yet boring activities. Despite this, there's still more content here than in DAoC. DAoC made an attempt to create a game with less of the boring stuff and more real gameplay. They succeeded, but don't have enough varied content to hold player's interest.<br>
<br>
The real &quot;king&quot; of the MMRPG market will be whomever develops a game with the scope of EQ, but without the boring timesinks (and who also has a large marketing budget :P ). I'm betting on World of Warcraft. Blizzard is probably the first game design company to approach this genre with sufficient talent, budget and experience to actually propel it beyond EQ.<br>
<br>
Who was it that said movies are simply real life with all the mundane parts taken out? It's true of MMRPGs too. <p><B>-Jullian</B></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/uwhizbangdustyboots.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Whizbang Dustyboots</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>O.G. (Original Gnome)</span><br>  Posts: 1070<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(4/29/02 2:32:23 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2434.topic&index=43>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.lby3.com/eq/whiz/flappy.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Be honest</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> Who was it that said movies are simply real life with all the mundane parts taken out? It's true of MMRPGs too.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->Remember that when you play Star Wars Galaxies. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
