--Tenken</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/usonicbeat00the00bard.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Sonicbeat00the00Bard</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 7<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(5/1/02 5:21:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub41.ezboard.com/fvazaellecommunitycenterfrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2434.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Be honest</span><hr size=1> EQ 2  seems to have the faults of EQ fixed. <br>
1. The economy in EQ sucks, all you do in EQ is put in. Money does not flow. By making things breakable, people who practice tradeskills have more use and money will actually be worth something.<br>
2. The graphics yes are high in performance, but show more realism.<br>
3. When specializing your character through level growth that is more of an RPG essence.<br>
4. Finally, the problem with EQ is gear and weapons keep on getting better when the next set comes out. Sure they say that the stats will change and the ac or damage /delay will not increase what it has been in the past, but that plan hasn't followed through. What is going to happen when you give your twink 100 ac bp and an 18/1 sword and get to level 60 in an hour?<br>
<br>
Food for thought.<br>
